Why do countries try to protect their own firms from exposure to the world market? Countries may try to protect their firms from exposure to the world market in order to shield them from foreign competition and to allow them to grow and become more competitive in the long run. Additionally, if a country's firms are able to grow and become more competitive in the global market, it may lead to an increase in the country's overall economic growth.

When are the benefits of free trade dispersed? The benefits of free trade are dispersed throughout the economy. Consumers benefit from lower prices and greater choice, while producers benefit from increased efficiency and the ability to sell their products in new markets.

Why would a country not want to put their own firms on the world market? There are a few reasons why a country might not want to put their firms on the world market. One reason is that the country's firms might not be competitive in the global market. Another reason is that the country might not want to give up control of its firms to foreign investors. Finally, the country might not want to open up its markets to foreign competition.
